definition: "Vitamin C (L-ascorbic acid) is a water-soluble essential vitamin — 'essential' meaning humans cannot synthesize it endogenously due to the absence of the enzyme L-gulonolactone oxidase (which catalyzes the final step of ascorbic acid synthesis in most other mammals). Dietary sources must supply all vitamin C requirements. Vitamin C functions primarily as: (1) a coenzyme for hydroxylase enzymes — most critically prolyl hydroxylase and lysyl hydroxylase, which are required for post-translational hydroxylation of proline and lysine residues in procollagen chains; without these modifications, the collagen triple helix cannot form properly, and the resulting defective collagen cannot cross-link, produces connective tissue failure (scurvy in severe deficiency); (2) a reducing agent and antioxidant — ascorbate donates electrons to neutralize reactive oxygen species, regenerates vitamin E from its oxidized form (tocopheryl radical), and is the primary water-soluble antioxidant in plasma; (3) an enhancer of non-heme iron absorption — ascorbate in the gut reduces ferric iron (Fe³⁺) to ferrous iron (Fe²⁺), the absorbable form, substantially increasing iron bioavailability from plant sources; and (4) a cofactor in neurotransmitter and hormone synthesis — including norepinephrine synthesis (dopamine beta-hydroxylase), carnitine synthesis, and peptide amidation."
why_it_matters: "Vitamin C deficiency sufficient to cause classical scurvy (perifollicular hemorrhage, corkscrew hairs, gingivitis, poor wound healing) is rare in high-income countries, but subclinical deficiency — plasma vitamin C below 11.4 µmol/L (2 mg/dL) or insufficiency below 28 µmol/L — is far more prevalent than most practitioners assume. NHANES data estimates that 5–15% of US adults have deficient plasma vitamin C, with higher rates in: smokers (who oxidize ascorbate at 2–3× the normal rate and have substantially lower plasma levels on equivalent intakes); older adults (reduced absorption and intake); people with limited fruit and vegetable consumption; and those with inflammatory conditions or metabolic syndrome. The functional consequences of subclinical insufficiency span collagen quality (affecting vascular wall integrity, wound healing, joint health), antioxidant capacity (reduced protection against oxidized LDL and vascular oxidative stress), and immune function. Multiple large cohort studies have found inverse associations between plasma vitamin C and cardiovascular disease risk, cancer risk, and all-cause mortality — though the causal direction is debated and may partly reflect the lifestyle pattern of people who consume adequate vitamin C."

