longevity_notes: "Plasma vitamin C reflects recent dietary intake more than tissue stores — it is susceptible to rapid decline with illness, stress, or even a few days of low vitamin C intake. Leukocyte vitamin C concentration is a better measure of tissue stores but is not routinely available. The standard reference range lower bound (0.4 mg/dL) is calibrated to prevent overt deficiency — functional insufficiency occurs above this level. The longevity-optimal range targets steady-state levels achievable with consistent dietary intake of ~200 mg/day from food. Very high-dose supplementation (> 1,000 mg/day) typically does not further elevate plasma levels above the saturation point (~70 µmol/L) because intestinal absorption becomes fractional at high doses and renal excretion increases; plasma levels plateau despite increasing doses."
