takeaways:
- "<strong>Smoking destroys vitamin C at 2–3× the normal rate — smokers need significantly more dietary vitamin C to maintain the same plasma levels as non-smokers.</strong> Cigarette smoke generates massive quantities of reactive oxygen species that oxidize ascorbate. Smokers have plasma vitamin C levels approximately 25–50% lower than non-smokers on identical dietary intakes. The Institute of Medicine RDA for smokers is therefore 35 mg/day higher than for non-smokers (105 mg/day for women who smoke, 125 mg/day for men who smoke) — but even these amounts may be insufficient to achieve the same plasma levels as non-smokers. This makes vitamin C status particularly important to measure and optimize in current or recent smokers."
- "<strong>Vitamin C is essential for collagen hydroxylation — without adequate C, collagen is structurally defective and arterial wall integrity is compromised.</strong> Prolyl and lysyl hydroxylase enzymes — which require vitamin C as a coenzyme — add hydroxyl groups to specific proline and lysine residues in procollagen. These modifications are required for the triple helix to form properly and for collagen fibrils to cross-link into stable connective tissue. The most life-threatening consequence of collagen defects (scurvy) is perivascular hemorrhage as weakened blood vessel walls rupture under normal pressure. At subclinical levels, suboptimal collagen quality affects arterial wall stiffness and resilience, wound healing rates, and joint cartilage maintenance."
- "<strong>Vitamin C substantially enhances non-heme iron absorption — relevant for anyone eating a predominantly plant-based diet.</strong> Non-heme iron (from plant sources) must be reduced from Fe³⁺ to Fe²⁺ in the gut for absorption. Vitamin C is the most potent known enhancer of this reduction — consuming 100 mg of vitamin C with a plant-based iron-containing meal can increase non-heme iron absorption by 2–4×. This interaction is particularly relevant for vegetarians, vegans, women with heavy menstrual blood loss, and anyone with borderline iron stores. Conversely, tea, coffee, and calcium consumed with iron-rich meals inhibit absorption; the practical advice is to include vitamin C-rich foods at iron-containing meals."
- "<strong>The Linus Pauling hypothesis — that very high-dose vitamin C prevents or treats cancer and cardiovascular disease — remains highly contested despite decades of research.</strong> Observational studies consistently find that higher dietary vitamin C is associated with lower cardiovascular and cancer risk, but these associations almost certainly reflect the overall dietary pattern (fruit and vegetable consumption) rather than vitamin C specifically. Randomized controlled trials of vitamin C supplementation have generally not demonstrated the dramatic health benefits Pauling proposed. The current scientific consensus is that adequate vitamin C (achievable from diet) supports health, but pharmacological megadoses (gram-level supplementation) do not clearly provide additional benefit beyond what food-level intake achieves for most people."
- "<strong>Vitamin C at high supplemental doses can mask iron overload by enhancing absorption — relevant for people with hemochromatosis or ferritin above normal.</strong> High-dose vitamin C supplementation substantially increases dietary non-heme iron absorption. In people with hereditary hemochromatosis (HFE gene mutations causing excessive iron absorption) or those with already-elevated ferritin, megadose vitamin C supplementation can accelerate iron loading. For anyone with ferritin above the normal range, high-dose vitamin C supplements (above 500 mg/day) should be used cautiously and with monitoring. This interaction does not apply to dietary vitamin C from food."

