<section class="bm-section">
<h2>Subclinical Vitamin C Insufficiency: More Common Than Appreciated</h2>

<p>Scurvy in its classical form — gum disease, perifollicular hemorrhage, impaired wound healing — captures attention because it is so dramatic and historically significant. But the population health burden from subclinical vitamin C insufficiency is far greater and largely invisible. NHANES surveys consistently find that 5–15% of US adults have plasma vitamin C in the deficient range, with many more in the subclinical insufficiency range.</p>

<p>The groups most affected are predictable: smokers (who oxidize ascorbate at 2–3× the rate of non-smokers); older adults with reduced dietary diversity; people living in food-insecure environments; and anyone relying heavily on processed foods rather than fresh produce. Given that a single red bell pepper or orange provides a day's worth of vitamin C, clinical deficiency in affluent populations reflects either severe dietary restriction, malabsorption, or smoking-driven oxidative depletion — not dietary unavailability.</p>

<p>The collagen synthesis impairment that begins before overt scurvy has clinical relevance: subclinical vitamin C insufficiency affects arterial wall collagen quality, wound healing rates, and capillary fragility in ways that may contribute to cardiovascular aging, impaired recovery from injury, and accelerated skin aging — none of which trigger a clinical diagnosis until the deficiency is advanced.</p>
</section>

<section class="bm-section">
<h2>Vitamin C in Cardiovascular Biology</h2>

<p>Vitamin C's relevance to cardiovascular aging operates through three mechanisms. First, endothelial nitric oxide — the primary vasodilatory signal in arteries — is protected from oxidative inactivation by ascorbate; adequate vitamin C helps preserve NO bioavailability and endothelial function. Second, LDL oxidation (a central step in atherogenesis) is inhibited by vitamin C in the aqueous phase of plasma and lipoproteins. Third, collagen integrity in arterial walls depends on vitamin C-dependent hydroxylation reactions — suboptimal C produces collagen with reduced mechanical strength.</p>

<p>These mechanisms align with observational data: the EPIC-Norfolk cohort study found that plasma vitamin C was inversely associated with all-cause and cardiovascular mortality in 20,000 adults, with the highest quartile of plasma C showing significantly lower event rates than the lowest quartile — an association that persisted after adjustment for other dietary factors. <sup><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11438133/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">1</a></sup></p>

